data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count, "Expected at least one user");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** ã on failure reports *both* values instead of just "expected True, got False"
- **`CollectionAssert`** ã has `AllItemsAreNotNull`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `Contains`, `AreEquivalent` (same items, any order), `AreEqual` (same items, same order)
- **`Assert.IsNotNull`** ã clearer intent than `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)`
- **Message parameters** ã add context to any assert for debugging

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
// Same items regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);

// Exact order matters
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);

// Subset check
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);

// Type checking
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));
```

> **Note:** `CollectionAssert` works on `ICollection`. If you have `IEnumerable`, call `.ToList()` first.
